Another way to do it, again depending on what else your code is doing, would be to use the `.assign` method:
```df = df[some_logical_condition].assign(sys_time=datetime.utcnow().strftime("%d/%m/%Y %I:%M:%S.%f"))```
Generally, methods like this always return a _new_ DataFrame. You can set multiple columns in one call:
```df = df[some_logical_condition].assign(sys_time=datetime.utcnow().strftime("%d/%m/%Y %I:%M:%S.%f"), x=y)```
You can also do a pipeline of methods, each returning a new DataFrame, e.g.
```        df = df.groupby(
            'I'
        ).apply(
            lambda g: g.set_index(
                'T'
            ).resample(
                '100ms'
            ).asfreq(

            ).drop(
                columns=['I']
            )
        ).reorder_levels(
            ['T', 'I']
        ).reset_index(

        ).sort_values(
            [
                'T',
                'I'
            ]
        )```

